README for ncep data reader
John Caron, caron@ucar.edu
doc last changed : 9/18/97
code changes:
    11/19/97: fix FLOAT=8 error

These routines read NCEP grib files, either local or on the NCAR Mass Store.
The interface is designed for MATCH.

This is not a general purpose grib reader, but specific to reading the
NCEP/NCAP reanalysis files into MATCH.  The Grib table used is specific to
this dataset.  The actual variables that it can read are based on what MATCH 
currently needs in order to run advection/convection/diffusion, and what NCEP 
can provide. These variables for Match (and their NCEP equivalents) are:

			match		NCEP
			-----		-----
  surface geopotential	phis 		9.80665 * HGT (3d)
  orography		oro		a mapping of ICEC and LAND (2d)
  surface pressure	ps		PRES (3d)
  specific humidity	q		SPFH, min 1.0e-12, max saturation q (3d)
  temperature		t		TMP (3d)
  horiz winds		uv		UGRD, VGRD (3d)
  surface temperature   ts		TMP (2d) <----------- was bad
  zonal surface stress  taux		UFLX (2d)
  meridional surface stress tauy	VFLX (2d)
  surface sensible heat flux hflx	SHTFL (2d)
  surface water vapor flux qflx		(LHTFL / 2.31e6) (2d)

	
Source Files:
    reader.F		fortran interface
    reader.inc		include common
    grib.[ch]		called by reader
    gribr.[ch]  	actual grib reader

    ../mss.[ch]		mass store files management
    ../str_util.[ch]	string utilities
    ../utim.[ch]	time conversion utilities
    ../rgi.[ch]		regridding routine
    ../rgip.F		to allow vectorization

    Note that you need the netcdf library for rgi.

Run time files: these files must exist in the current working directory
   of the running program. All exist in readers/ncep/data directory.

    grib.table2.rean	table of NCEP/NCAR reanalysis grib parameters, obtained 
			from ftp://wesley.wwb.noaa.gov/pub/wgrib/kpds5.v21.Z
    grb2d.list  	list of ncep 2d grib files, in sequential order
    grbsanl.list  	list of ncep 3d grib "grbsanl" files, in sequential order
    T62n.T42n.avg.nc	a netcdf file used to convert T62 to T42 grid


Mass Store Management

    The list of ncep files are in the following blank-delimited format:
	    	<filename> <size> <starting_time>
       The time is in "unix seconds", seconds since 1/1/70 0Z
       I have generated such a list from the mass store files at NCAR (1/90 to 8/96)
       The actual files available start in 1973.
			
    The mss.c routines do the following:
	  1) check if the file exists in local path, and that file sizes match.
	  2) if not, generates a call to the mass store (e.g. mssread on the CRAY)
	     to get it. The mass store system is responsible for un-COS blocking it.
	  3) optionally waits until the file arrives.  It checks the file size to make
	     sure that all of it has been transferred.
  	  
    The grib.c routines do the following:
	  1) As requests are made, fetch the mss files as needed.
	  2) "look ahead" one mss file, so we never have to wait
	  3) only keep current and next files; delete older ones.
	  4) interpolate and reorder the data as requested.

    The gribr.c routines do the following:
	  1) when opening a file, read through all headers and create an index file
	     af all the products = field, level, time.  The index file is called
	     <filename>.index.  If it already exists, use it. The last line of the
	     index file has "DONE-DONE-DONE" to eliminate aborted reads.
	  2) The files are actually tar files, but gribr ignores that fact, and simply
	     locates the grib record inside the tar file.
	  3) Read and convert the grib records into floating point arrays.


Regridding
	The reader optionally regrids the NCEP T62 grid to T42 (actually it could be
	any other grid, but currently set up for T42)

	We use an area-weighted average algorithm. Intersections in lat/lon space are 
	done as simple rectangles, then areas are computed using 
		dlon * (sin(lat2) - sin(lat1)).
	The sum of the fractional intersections always add up to 1.0.  These weights 
	are precalculated by the program rg_2netcdf, which stores them in the netcdf 
	file T62.T42.avg.nc.

	The call to grib_open has a parameter that controls whether to regrid or not.
